explanation:
mhd_tool_get_system_cpu_count — required to know possible return values and side effects; whether it can ever return >0 (so the main "detected" branch is reachable) and whether it has side effects that make its calls non-dead.
mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count — required to know possible return values and side effects for the fallback path and whether its results can change control flow (so the fallback logic and associated prints are not dead).
mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_special_api_, mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysctl_, mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysconf_, mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysctl_fallback_, mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysconf_fallback_ — internal callees of mhd_tool_get_system_cpu_count; needed to determine the full range of system-CPU results and any side effects that affect reachability of branches in detect_cpu_core_count.
mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_sched_getaffinity_, mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_cpuset_getaffinity_, mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_sched_getaffinity_np_, mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_w32_ — internal callees of mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count; needed to determine whether proc-count fallbacks can produce >0 and thus make the fallback branch (and its prints/assignments) semantically necessary.
MHD_REAL_CPU_COUNT — compile-time macro that controls an entire fallback branch; its presence/value determines whether that code is compiled in and whether the branch can ever change behaviour.
fprintf, printf — I/O functions invoked for diagnostics; needed to assess side effects (observable behaviour) so we can decide whether removing those calls would change program behaviour (i.e., whether they are dead).
get_cpu_core_count — direct caller of detect_cpu_core_count; required to determine whether detect_cpu_core_count is ever invoked in the program (if never called, the whole function could be dead).
detect_process_cpu_core_count, get_num_threads, check_apply_param__all_cpus, check_apply_param__threads, init_data — callers of get_cpu_core_count (transitive callers); included to establish a call path from program entry to detect_cpu_core_count and to determine reachability in the whole program (necessary to decide whether the function or parts of it are dead).
